   Gradient Descent:-
   ğŸ“Œ How Does It Work?
    ğŸ”¹ Step 1: Start with random values for m (slope) and c (intercept) in the equation y = mx + c.
    ğŸ”¹ Step 2: Compute the Loss Function (Mean Squared Error - MSE).
    ğŸ”¹ Step 3: Calculate the gradient (derivative) of the loss function to determine the direction of update.
    ğŸ”¹ Step 4: Update m and c using the formula:

    m=mâˆ’Î± (âˆ‚j/âˆ‚m)
    c=câˆ’Î± (âˆ‚j/âˆ‚c)
    
    Where Î± (learning rate) controls the step size.

    ğŸ”¹ Step 5: Repeat until loss is minimized and the model finds the best-fitting line!


  âœ… Why is Gradient Descent Important?
    âœ”ï¸ Helps in optimizing model parameters to minimize error.
    âœ”ï¸ Efficient for large datasets where direct computation isn't feasible.
    âœ”ï¸ Essential for deep learning and complex models.

  âœ… Advantages:

    âœ”ï¸ Easy to implement & interpret.
    âœ”ï¸ Performs well when the data has a linear relationship.

  âŒ Disadvantages:

    âš ï¸ Not suitable for non-linear data.
    âš ï¸ Can underfit if important variables are missing.
    âš ï¸ Sensitive to outliers, which can impact predictions.


Logistic Regression:-

 ğŸ”¹ What is Logistic Regression?
      A supervised learning algorithm used for binary classification (e.g., spam vs. not spam, disease vs. no disease)
     Uses the Sigmoid Function to map predictions between 0 and 1

  ğŸ” Key Learnings:
    ğŸ“Œ Unlike Linear Regression, Logistic Regression predicts probabilities
    ğŸ“Œ The Sigmoid Function helps convert linear outputs into probabilities
    ğŸ“Œ Common applications: Email spam detection, medical diagnosis, fraud detection

  ğŸ“ˆ Sigmoid Function Formula:

